{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12006"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12006"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.78,0,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4593"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90010"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1341"},{"type":"tags","id":"3100"},{"type":"tags","id":"3300"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39924"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter, who is concerned about her mother\u0027s ability to care for herself at home, which appears to have been gradually deteriorating over the past 12 months. The patient admits that her memory is not what it used to be but believes she is coping well. She has been living independently for 10 years following her husband\u0027s death, with visits from her daughter three to four times a week. Recently, there have been some worrying situations, including forgetting that her daughter was coming over for dinner, and food burning on the stove while she was watching TV in another room. Additionally, the house is not as clean as usual, despite increasing help. She has a medical history of hypertension, diabetes and a previous hysterectomy. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide and enalapril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination is unremarkable, including no rigidity or tremor. When asked to do a Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE), the patient turns to her daughter for help with the day of the week and date, and scores 1/3 in recall, with a total MMSE score of 20. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the cognitive impairment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal ageing","Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Hypothyroidism","Vascular dementia","Medication side effects"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description fits for a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E. It is the most common form of dementia, characterised by deficits in memory and at least one other cognitive domain. Attention is often one of the last cognitive domains to deteriorate in Alzheimer\u0027s, helping differentiate between the types of dementia. It is associated with accumulation of amyloid and tau deposits within the brain. Short term memory is the earliest sign in Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, although there are other variants that may affect other domains progressively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal ageing\u003C/strong\u003E can involve some mild cognitive changes, but not to the extent described here. The patient\u0027s forgetfulness is causing safety concerns (leaving food burning on the stove) and affecting her ability to maintain her usual level of self-care and household management. These changes are more significant than what would be expected in normal ageing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause cognitive impairment, but it typically presents with other symptoms such as fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, and dry skin. The gradual onset and progressive nature of the symptoms described are more consistent with a neurodegenerative process like Alzheimer\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by cerebrovascular disease and brain ischemia. There are various subtypes, including multi-infarct dementia, hypoperfusion dementia and haemorrhagic dementia among others. Patients typically present with issues in executive dysfunction involving complex planning. The pathology here is the brain ischemia, usually from numerous smaller infarctions over time. Risk factors follow cardiovascular risk factors such as hypertension, smoking, diabetes and dyslipidemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedication side effects\u003C/strong\u003E can certainly cause cognitive impairment, especially in older adults. However, the medications listed (metformin, gliclazide, and enalapril) are not typically associated with significant cognitive side effects. Moreover, the gradual onset and progressive nature of the symptoms are more suggestive of a neurodegenerative process rather than medication-induced cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the progressive memory decline, particularly affecting short-term memory and recall, along with difficulties in daily functioning, strongly suggest Alzheimer\u0027s disease as the most likely diagnosis. The patient\u0027s difficulty with orientation to time and poor recall on the MMSE further support this diagnosis. It\u0027s important to note that while this clinical picture is highly suggestive of Alzheimer\u0027s disease, a definitive diagnosis would require further cognitive testing, neuroimaging, and potentially biomarker studies to rule out other causes of cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Various dementia types have vastly different treatments so the ability to clinically diagnose is important to begin therapy.","Alzheimer\u0027s disease typically presents with progressive memory loss, particularly affecting short-term memory and recall.","Careful history-taking, including collateral information from family members, is crucial in diagnosing dementia."],"references":["Falk N, Cole A, Meredith TJ. Evaluation of Suspected Dementia. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Mar 15;97(6):398-405. PMID: 29671539. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2018/0315/p398.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90010"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12006"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90010"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:09:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:11:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4593"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descripti